    Merged #143 RS-614: Add dummy patch operations to report service in franklin-ai/rosalind

    JIRA Reference

    https://franklin-ai.atlassian.net/browse/RS-614

    Change Summary

    Adds dummy patch "comment" operations to the report service.

    It uses https://jsonpatch.com/ approach , aka https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc6902 & https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc7396 . To implement this appropriately, https://crates.io/crates/json-patch needs to be added to the ros-models. A custom build.rs has been used for the client generator, so that it is using progenitor main, and using ros_models for most models, but generating the structs+impls for json_patch::Patch.

    See https://stackoverflow.com/questions/62358406/how-to-update-resources-with-patch-method-using-openapi-correctly for some thoughts on this.

    Code Review

    Concerns

    Checklist

    General

    • Does the implementation satisfy the requirements?
    • Beyond linting, is the code easy to read and understand? Are naming choices appropriate, descriptive and consistent with other parts of the system?
    • Is the code tested, and do the tests adequately cover the requirements?
    • Is the code documented?
    • Are there any hard coded configuration items?
    • Is the code tightly coupled to other systems, in a way that would make it difficult to maintain?
    • Is the code using new external libraries, that have not been captured and assessed as part of the SOUP management process?
    • Are there obvious security vulnerabilities; eg: use of free text passwords/keys
    • Is there any unnecessary duplication, either within the change, or of an existing module or standard library?
    • Is the data structure choice appropriate?
    • Does the code have any memory leaks? e.g. data structures that are continually added to, but never removed from?
    • Has thought been given to handling of exceptions?
    • Is the logging adequate for debugging in production?

    Performance

    • Is the difference in performance well understood; i.e. before and after performance improvement?
    • Is the optimization worth the additional complexity?

    See the Pull Requests for more info.

  • 3/8/23, 5:28 AM
    Commented on #143 POC: Add dummy patch operations to report service from franklin-ai/rosalind

    Right. This approach will have more endpoints & custom data structures.

    And yes to avoid additional endpoints/data structures, we'll be tempted to have the frontend repost content to the backend which contains unmodified content, such as lists which contain some unchanged members and others that are new/removed/modified, and then the backend needs to figure out what data changed in order to serialise the changes. The JSON patch approach means changes are "pre-wrapped" in the frontend in a format that describes the changes more accurately so the backend becomes more of slave of the front, of course still doing a bit of validation to enforce business rules, but otherwise processing packets of change as requested by the frontend.

  • 3/8/23, 5:00 AM
    Reviewed #143 POC: Add dummy patch operations to report service in franklin-ai/rosalind
  • 3/8/23, 5:00 AM
    Commented on #143 POC: Add dummy patch operations to report service from franklin-ai/rosalind

    In this approach, the objective is to be generic, and conforming to JSON Patch RFC, so that both frontend and backend can use the JSON Patch libraries to create diffs / ops & to do merges. We will add business rules to the backend to prevent inappropriate ops, but getting those rules into the emitted OAS document will be tricky (probably doable in the future, but will require extra voodoo with our OAS generator (https://crates.io/crates/utoipa) which is unlikely to be done in this milestone.

    If we want less generic now, we need to use the other approach (i.e. the one used for specimen), where we manually define each field modification which will be permitted.

    Change Summary

    Adds dummy patch "comment" operations to the report service.

    Two different approaches are show. One which requires custom structs be built for each model being modified. To implement this, we would need something like https://crates.io/crates/optional_struct added to the ros-models .

    The other is to use https://jsonpatch.com/ approach , aka https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc6902 & https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc7396 . To implement this appropriately, https://crates.io/crates/json-patch needs to be added to the ros-models.

    Code Review

    Concerns

    Checklist

    General

    • Does the implementation satisfy the requirements?
    • Beyond linting, is the code easy to read and understand? Are naming choices appropriate, descriptive and consistent with other parts of the system?
    • Is the code tested, and do the tests adequately cover the requirements?
    • Is the code documented?
    • Are there any hard coded configuration items?
    • Is the code tightly coupled to other systems, in a way that would make it difficult to maintain?
    • Is the code using new external libraries, that have not been captured and assessed as part of the SOUP management process?
    • Are there obvious security vulnerabilities; eg: use of free text passwords/keys
    • Is there any unnecessary duplication, either within the change, or of an existing module or standard library?
    • Is the data structure choice appropriate?
    • Does the code have any memory leaks? e.g. data structures that are continually added to, but never removed from?
    • Has thought been given to handling of exceptions?
    • Is the logging adequate for debugging in production?

    Bugfix

    • Does the change contain a test that would fail, if the bug was reintroduced?
    • Does the change address potentially related bugs? e.g. if the bug was caused by some user input error, does the fix address other possible invalid input?
    • Has the bug been fixed system wide? e.g. are there other parts of the code base with the same issue? Does the fix push the problem to another part of the system by mistake?

    Performance

    • Is the difference in performance well understood; i.e. before and after performance improvement?
    • Is the optimization worth the additional complexity?

    See the Pull Requests for more info.
